DPDPA Video Compliance Pipeline — Setup & Usage Guide
======================================================

This guide is for anyone setting up the project on a new machine.


══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 1 — PREREQUISITES (install once)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. Python 3.11
   Download: https://www.python.org/downloads/
   Tick "Add Python to PATH" during install.

2. Docker Desktop
   Download: https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/
   Start Docker Desktop before running the pipeline.

3. Git
   Download: https://git-scm.com/downloads

4. FFmpeg (required for video processing)
   From the project root in PowerShell:
   .\install_ffmpeg.ps1


══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 2 — FIRST-TIME SETUP (run once after cloning)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

All commands run from the project root folder in PowerShell.

Step 1 — Start Docker containers

    .\start.ps1 docker

    Wait ~30 seconds. Verify all containers are running:
    docker ps

    Expected: postgres, redis, minio, weaviate, ollama, flower all show "Up"

Step 2 — Create your .env file

    copy backend\.env.example backend\.env

    No edits needed for local development — the defaults work with Docker.

Step 3 — Create Python virtual environment

    python -m venv .venv
    .\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

    (Your prompt will show (.venv) when active)

Step 4 — Install Python dependencies

    pip install -r backend\requirements-minimal.txt

    This takes 5-15 minutes the first time (downloads AI models ~2 GB).

Step 4b — Pull LLaVA vision model for OCR (one-time, ~4 GB download)

    docker exec -it regtech_ollama ollama pull llava:7b

    This enables vision-language OCR for PII detection (PAN cards, Aadhaar, phone numbers)
    on video frames. LLaVA is a multimodal model that handles motion blur, overlays,
    and varied lighting better than traditional OCR engines.

    NOTE: LLaVA runs on CPU by default (~2-3 min per frame). For production use a
    GPU-enabled host. On CPU the pipeline will be slow for long videos.

    If you skip this step, the pipeline falls back to EasyOCR automatically.
    You can pull the model later and set OLLAMA_OCR_MODEL=llava:7b in backend/.env,
    then restart the worker — it will auto-detect it.

    To disable vision OCR and use EasyOCR instead, set:
    OLLAMA_OCR_MODEL=   (leave empty in backend/.env)

Step 5 — Run database migrations

    cd backend
    alembic upgrade head
    cd ..

    This creates all PostgreSQL tables.

Step 6 — Start the API server (Terminal 1)

    .\start.ps1 api

    Wait until you see: "Application startup complete."
    API is available at: http://localhost:8000
    API docs at:         http://localhost:8000/docs

Step 7 — Load DPDPA compliance rules (one-time, do this while API is running)

    $reloadParams = @{
        Uri    = "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/compliance/guidelines/reload"
        Method = "POST"
    }
    Invoke-RestMethod @reloadParams

    Expected response: { "message": "Guidelines reload complete", "pg_inserted": 5, ... }

Setup is complete.


══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 3 — DAILY USAGE
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════


Terminal 1 — Start Docker (if not already running)

    .\start.ps1 docker

Terminal 2 — Start API server

    .\start.ps1 api

Terminal 3 — Start Celery worker (processes videos in background)

    .\start.ps1 worker


Terminal 4
To check the health

Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8000/health/detailed"


— Submit a video and run compliance check

    --- Step A: Upload video ---
  $uploadParams = @{
    Uri         = "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/videos/upload"
    Method      = "POST"
    ContentType = "application/json"
    Body        = (@{ video_path = "C:/Users/mailt/OneDrive/Desktop/testvideo/nevideo30march.mp4" } | ConvertTo-Json)
}
$result = Invoke-RestMethod @uploadParams
$result
$videoId = $result.video_id

    Replace the video_path with the actual path to your video file.

    IMPORTANT — Path format in JSON:
    Always use FORWARD SLASHES (/) in the video_path, not backslashes (\).
    Windows accepts both, but JSON treats backslash as an escape character.

    CORRECT:   "C:/Users/mailt/Desktop/video.mp4"
    INCORRECT: "C:\Users\mailt\Desktop\video.mp4"  ← causes JSON decode error

    --- Step B: Poll until processing is complete ---
    Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/videos/$videoId/status"

    Repeat until status = "completed" (takes 2-5 minutes).

    The response now includes a pipeline_stages breakdown, e.g.:
    {
      "status": "completed",
      "pipeline_stages": {
        "frame_extraction": { "status": "completed", "frames": 50 },
        "ocr":              { "status": "completed", "engine": "easyocr",
                              "frames_with_text": 12, "ocr_coverage_pct": 24.0 },
        "visual":           { "status": "completed", "persons_detected": 3 },
        "transcription":    { "status": "completed", "segments": 8 }
      }
    }

    If ocr.status = "degraded" or ocr_coverage_pct = 0, OCR failed and
    PII text was not checked. See Troubleshooting section.

    --- Step C: Run DPDPA compliance check ---
    $checkParams = @{
        Uri    = "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/compliance/check/$videoId"
        Method = "POST"
    }
    Invoke-RestMethod @checkParams

    --- Step D: Fetch the full compliance report ---
    Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/compliance/report/$videoId"

    The report shows: compliance score, status, all violations found, evidence, and recommendations.

    IMPORTANT — Check data_quality before trusting the score:
    {
      "data_quality": {
        "ocr_verified": true,
        "score_reliable": true,
        "limitations": [],
        "warning": null
      }
    }

    If ocr_verified = false or score_reliable = false, OCR was unavailable during
    analysis. The score may be falsely high — text-based PII (Aadhaar, PAN, phone
    numbers shown on screen) was NOT checked. Fix OCR and re-run the compliance check.


══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SECTION 4 — USEFUL COMMANDS
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Re-process a video from scratch (wipes old data):
    Body = '{"video_path": "...", "force": true}'

Reload DPDPA rules after code changes:
    Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/compliance/guidelines/reload" -Method POST

Check Docker container health:
    docker ps

Restart a specific container (e.g. weaviate):
    docker restart regtech_weaviate

View API documentation (Swagger UI):
    http://localhost:8000/docs

View MinIO storage console:
    http://localhost:9001   (login: minioadmin / minioadmin)

View Celery task monitor (Flower):
    http://localhost:5555
    Shows all tasks: pending, running, completed, failed, retry count, timing.
    Use this to debug stuck or slow videos in real time.

View full audit trail for a compliance report:
    Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "http://localhost:8000/api/v1/compliance/audit/$reportId"
    Returns every step the compliance pipeline executed — what it checked, what it found,
    and whether each step succeeded or failed.


