SECTION 5 — USING THE WEB UI
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The web UI is a single HTML file at frontend/index.html.
Open it directly in any browser — no web server required.

    File location: frontend\index.html
    Open with:     Double-click the file, or drag it into Chrome / Edge / Firefox.
    API must be running at http://localhost:8000 before using the UI.


— Before you open the UI, start the backend services:

    Terminal 1 — Docker infrastructure
        .\start.ps1 docker

    Terminal 2 — API server
        .\start.ps1 api

    Terminal 3 — Celery worker (processes videos in background)
        .\start.ps1 worker


— Step-by-step: upload and process a video via the UI

    Step 1 — Start infrastructure (PowerShell from project root)

        .\start.ps1 docker

        Wait ~30 seconds. Confirm all containers are running:
        docker ps   (all six should show "Up")

    Step 2 — Start the API server (new terminal)

        .\start.ps1 api

        Wait until you see: "Application startup complete."

    Step 3 — Start the Celery worker (new terminal)

        .\start.ps1 worker

        Wait for the startup checks table to print.
        All items must show OK ✓  (OCR may show WARN ! — that is acceptable).

    Step 4 — Open the UI

        Double-click frontend\index.html in File Explorer.
        It opens in your default browser. No web server needed.

    Step 5 — Drop or browse your video

        Drag a video file onto the centre upload area,
        or click "Browse Files" to pick one from your computer.
        Supported formats: MP4, MOV, AVI, MKV, WEBM.

    Step 6 — Click "ANALYSE VIDEO"

        The file uploads to the API server.
        The upload card locks and shows "PIPELINE ACTIVE".
        Do not refresh the page while processing is running.

    Step 7 — Watch processing (takes 2–5 minutes)

        Left panel  — Pipeline Log updates with timestamped events.
        Stage chips — FRAMES → OCR → VISUAL → AUDIO light up orange
                      while running, then turn green when done.
        Progress bar fills to 100% as the pipeline advances.

    Step 8 — Read results (right panel, appears automatically)

        • Compliance score ring (0–100, colour-coded)
        • Pass / Fail / Critical violation counts
        • Full violation list with severity and rule references
        • Yellow warning if OCR was unavailable (score may be incomplete)

    Step 9 — Export the report

        Click JSON, CSV, or TXT in the right panel to download.
        JSON — full machine-readable report (all fields and findings)
        CSV  — violations only (Severity, Rule, Timestamp, Description)
        TXT  — human-readable summary with recommendations

    Step 10 — To analyse another video

        Click "Remove" on the locked file card.
        The UI resets. Repeat from Step 5.


— If something goes wrong:

    Upload fails (red border on file card)
        → API server not running — go back to Step 2.
        → Celery worker not started — go back to Step 3.
        → Error message on the card will tell you the exact cause.

    Stage chips stop updating after ~5 minutes
        → Open http://localhost:5555 (Flower) to inspect the task.
        → Check Active / Reserved tabs for your task.

    Score is 0% with a stage failure warning
        → Check the worker terminal for the specific error message.
        → Fix the issue, then re-upload with Remove → re-drop → Analyse.


— UI layout overview:

    Left panel   — Pipeline Log: timestamped event stream for the active job.
    Centre panel — Upload card, stage chips, and progress bar.
    Right panel  — Compliance results and export buttons (shown after analysis).


— Important notes:

    • The UI communicates directly with http://localhost:8000.
      If the API is not running, uploads will fail immediately.

    • If upload fails (red border on the file card): check that the API server
      is running and that the Celery worker is started (.\start.ps1 worker).
      The error message on the card tells you what went wrong.

    • If the pipeline stalls (stage chips don't progress after ~5 minutes):
      open http://localhost:5555 (Flower) to inspect the task status.

    • OCR warning in results: if the right panel shows "OCR was unavailable",
      text-based PII (Aadhaar, PAN, phone numbers on screen) was not checked.
      Fix OCR (see Section 5 — Troubleshooting) and re-upload the video.

    • The UI works from file:// — you do not need Node.js or a local web server.


